{"title_page": "Lucius Junius Brutus Damasippus", "text_new": "'''Lucius Junius Brutus Damasippus''' was a [[Roman Republic|Roman]] commander during [[Sulla]]\u2019s civil wars.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=The collapse of Rome : Marius, Sulla and the first Civil War, 91-70 BC|last=Sampson, Gareth C.|isbn=9781473826854|location=Barnsley, South Yorkshire|oclc=893910287|date = 2013-09-09}}</ref> When [[Pompey]] rebelled Brutus was one of the three commanders sent against him.<ref name=\":0\" /> In an unnamed battle, the first of Pompey\u2019s career, Brutus was defeated.<ref name=\":0\" /> When [[Optimates|Sullan]] forces defeated their opponents Brutus massacred many neutral senators to prevent them from welcoming Sulla.<ref name=\":0\" /> In the [[Second battle of Clusium]] Brutus and one of the last remaining [[Populares|Marian]] forces were heavily defeated.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=The Gracchi Marius and Sulla|last=Beesley|first=A. H.|publisher=Pinnacle Press|year=2017|isbn=978-1374894761|location=|pages=}}</ref> The defeated Marian commanders went to the [[Samnites]], with whom they marched on [[Rome]], but were defeated<ref name=\":1\" /> outside its gates by forces led by Sulla and [[Marcus Licinius Crassus|Crassus]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n[[Category:Ancient Roman generals]]\n", "text_old": "'''Lucius Junius Brutus Damasippus''' was a [[Roman Republic|Roman]] commander during [[Sulla]]\u2019s civil wars.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=The collapse of Rome : Marius, Sulla and the first Civil War, 91-70 BC|last=Sampson, Gareth C.|isbn=9781473826854|location=Barnsley, South Yorkshire|oclc=893910287|date = 2013-09-09}}</ref> When [[Pompey]] rebelled Brutus was on of the three commanders sent against him.<ref name=\":0\" /> In an unnamed battle, the first of Pompey\u2019s career, Brutus was defeated.<ref name=\":0\" /> When [[Optimates|Sullan]] forces defeated their opponents Brutus massacred many neutral senators to prevent them from welcoming Sulla.<ref name=\":0\" /> In the [[Second battle of Clusium]] Brutus and one of the last remaining [[Populares|Marian]] forces were heavily defeated.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=The Gracchi Marius and Sulla|last=Beesley|first=A. H.|publisher=Pinnacle Press|year=2017|isbn=978-1374894761|location=|pages=}}</ref> The defeated Marian commanders went to the [[Samnites]], with whom they marched on [[Rome]], but were defeated<ref name=\":1\" /> outside its gates by forces led by Sulla and [[Marcus Licinius Crassus|Crassus]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n[[Category:Ancient Roman generals]]\n", "name_user": "Saehyu", "label": "safe", "comment": "\"When Pompey rebelled Brutus was on of the three commanders sent against him.\" - Should be 'one', not \"on\".", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lucius_Junius_Brutus_Damasippus"}
{"title_page": "The Rugrats Movie", "text_new": "{{about|the movie|the video game|The Rugrats Movie (video game)}}\n{{Use American English|date = March 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Rugrats Movie\n| image          = File:This_is_the_Theatrical_Release_Poster_of_the_Rugrats_Movie.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| directors      = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Igor Kovalyov]]\n* Norton Virgien\n}}\n| producers      = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Arlene Klasky]]\n* [[G\u00e1bor Csup\u00f3]]\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* [[David N. Weiss]]\n* J. David Stem\n}}\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[Rugrats]]''|Arlene Klasky<br />Gabor Csupo<br />[[Paul Germain]]}}\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n* [[E. G. Daily]]\n* [[Tara Strong]]\n* [[Christine Cavanaugh]]\n* [[Kath Soucie]]\n* [[Cheryl Chase (actress)|Cheryl Chase]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Mark Mothersbaugh]]<ref name=AFIRugrats>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/DetailView.aspx?s=&Movie=61550|title=Detail view of Movies Page|work=afi.com|accessdate=May 16, 2015}}</ref>\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* John Bryant\n* Kimberly Rettberg\n}}\n| production companies = [[Klasky Csupo]]<ref name=AFIRugrats/>\n| distributor    = {{plainlist|\n* [[Paramount Pictures]]<ref name=AFIRugrats/>\n* [[Nickelodeon Movies]]<ref name=AFIRugrats/>\n}}\n| released       = {{Film date|1998|11|20}}\n| runtime        = 80 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 80:02--><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/rugrats-movie-1970-3 | title=''The Rugrats Movie'' (U) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=December 16, 1998 | accessdate=August 28, 2016}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $24 million\n| gross          = $140.9 million\n}}\n'''''The Rugrats Movie''''' is a 1998 American [[Animation|animated]] [[adventure]] [[comedy film]] based on the [[Nickelodeon]]\nanimated television series ''[[Rugrats]]''. It was directed by [[Igor Kovalyov]] and Norton Virgien and written by [[David N. Weiss]] & J. David Stem.<ref name=\"The Rugrats Movie\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/443844/Rugrats-Movie-The/full-credits.html|title=The Rugrats Movie|work=[[Turner Classic Movies]]|publisher=[[Turner Broadcasting System]] ([[Time Warner]])|location=[[Atlanta]]|accessdate=November 10, 2016}}</ref> The film introduced [[Tommy Pickles]]' baby brother [[Dil Pickles]], who appeared on the original series the next year. The film features the voices of [[E. G. Daily]], [[Tara Strong]], [[Christine Cavanaugh]], [[Kath Soucie]], [[Cheryl Chase (actress)|Cheryl Chase]], [[Cree Summer]], and [[Charlie Adler]], along with guest stars [[David Spade]], [[Whoopi Goldberg]], [[Margaret Cho]], [[Busta Rhymes]], and [[Tim Curry]]. The events of the film take place before the [[List of Rugrats episodes|sixth season]] of ''Rugrats''.\n\nPlans for a Rugrats film adaptation, along with [[Ren and Stimpy]] and [[Doug (series)|Doug]], began when Nickelodeon made a contract with [[20th Century Fox]] to produce films between 1993 and 1995.<ref name=\":0\" /> However, the contract expired with no films into production. Around the same year when contract expired, development of the film restarted with [[Paramount Pictures]] since Nick's parent company, [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]], purchased the studio in 1994. \n\nThe film holds the distinction for being the first animated film from [[Nickelodeon Movies]], as well as the first to be based on a Nicktoon. Paramount Pictures originally released it in the United States on November 20, 1998.<ref name=AFIRugrats/> The film received mixed to positive reviews from critics and grossed $141 million worldwide.\n\n==Plot==\n[[Didi Pickles]] is [[pregnancy|pregnant]] with her second baby, which she believes will be a girl while everyone else believes it will be a boy. Didi goes into labor during her baby shower and her friends rush her to the hospital. While this is happening, the kids crawl off and explore a nursery area before being found by the other parents. When the baby is finally born after a montage of [[Reincarnation|past lives]], it turns out to a boy and they name him [[Dil Pickles|Dil]].\n\nDil quickly becomes a very spoiled and mean baby, crying non-stop for attention, not listening to his mom and dad, keeping all of the toys for himself, and refusing to share with [[Tommy Pickles|Tommy]]. After a nasty fight between Tommy and Dil over Tommy's teddy bear, their father, [[Stu Pickles|Stu]] has a conversation with him about being a big brother and the responsibility he now has, assuring him that one day he will be happy to have Dil as his little brother. He also gives Tommy a locket with a picture of Tommy and Dil taped together and a watch inside, which he calls his \"sponsitility\" (his term for responsibility).\n\nWhen Dil pushes the other babies too far, they decide to take him back to the hospital despite Tommy's disapproval, and end up driving recklessly through the streets in a [[Reptar]] Wagon which Stu had built for a contest. Along the way, Dil secretly steals [[Angelica Pickles|Angelica's]] Cynthia doll, which prompts her to take the family dog, [[List of Rugrats characters|Spike]] and they embark on a quest to find the babies and retrieve Cynthia.\n\nThe babies eventually crash in the woods, where they realize that they are lost. They spot a ranger's cabin where they believe a \"lizard\" (a mispronunciation of [[wizard (fantasy)|wizard]]) lives, and decide to go there, believing that it can take them home. After an encounter with a gang of runaway circus monkeys, Dil is taken away by them. Tommy vows to find Dil by himself, after [[Chuckie Finster|Chuckie]], [[Phil and Lil]] agree they are better off without him.\n\nMeanwhile, the parents find out that the babies are missing and try to find them. However, it becomes a media sensation with numerous news reporters constantly asking the adults questions and intentionally enrages Stu's brother [[Drew Pickles|Drew]] into attacking Stu by telling him he lost Angelica.\n\nTommy eventually finds Dil during a storm, and are forced to take shelter under a tree. But as Tommy tries to take care of him, Dil selfishly drinks all of the milk and keeps the large blanket for himself, which leads to the blanket tearing in half and Tommy falling into a puddle of mud. Tommy finally snaps and nearly pours banana baby food on Dil for the monkeys to take him away, but Tommy's rage and the storm's lightning and thunder scare Dil so much that he sees the error of his ways. They reconcile and sleep peacefully.\n\nAfter the storm, the other babies find Tommy and Dil, and after running into Angelica and Spike they make their way to the \"lizard\". While on a bridge, they are confronted by the monkeys, but are then scared off by a scary [[wolf]] who's been hunting down the babies since they arrived in the woods. Spike intervenes and fights the wolf until they both fall from the bridge. Meanwhile, Stu, who has been looking for the babies via a [[pterodactyl]]-like aircraft he made, finally finds them, but crash lands into the ranger's cabin. Believing he is the \"lizard,\" the babies wish for Spike back instead of going home. Stu falls through the bridge and finds Spike, who actually survived the fall by landing on a strut of the bridge. The babies are then reunited with their families, and the monkeys with their circus owners. The monkeys attack Rex Pester, the most obnoxious of all the news reporters, much to Betty and Charlotte's amusement. Dil finally learns to share when he drinks half of a bottle of formula and gives the other half to Tommy. The families return home and the babies accept Dil as one of the group after he assists them in getting an ice cream sundae form the top shelf of the refrigerator.\n\nIn a [[post-credits scene]], Grandpa Lou is sleeping in the Reptar Wagon when Grandpa Boris' goat kicks it, sending both the wagon and Grandpa down the street and presumably starting another adventure all over again.\n\n==Cast==\n{{main article|List of Rugrats characters}}\n===Main===\n* [[E. G. Daily]] as [[Tommy Pickles]]\n* [[Tara Strong]] as Dil Pickles\n* [[Christine Cavanaugh]] as Chuckie Finster\n* [[Kath Soucie]] as Phil, Lil, and Betty DeVille\n* [[Cheryl Chase (actress)|Cheryl Chase]] as [[Angelica Pickles]]\n* [[Cree Summer]] as Susie Carmichael\n\n===Supporting===\n* [[Jack Riley (actor)|Jack Riley]] as Stu Pickles\n* [[Joe Alaskey]] as Grandpa Lou Pickles\n* [[Melanie Chartoff]] as Didi Pickles and Grandma Minka\n* [[Michael Bell (actor)|Michael Bell]] as Drew Pickles, Chas<!--Closing credits list the character as Chas, not Chaz--> Finster and Grandpa Boris\n* [[Tress MacNeille]] as Charlotte Pickles\n* [[Philip Proctor|Phil Proctor]] as Howard DeVille\n\n===Guest===\n* [[David Spade]] as Ranger Frank\n* [[Whoopi Goldberg]] as Ranger Margaret\n* [[Tim Curry]] as Rex Pester\n* [[Hattie Winston]] as Dr. Lucy Carmichael\n* [[Andrea Martin]] as Aunt Miriam\n* [[Busta Rhymes]] as Reptar Wagon\n* [[Roger Clinton, Jr.]] as Air Crewman\n* [[Margaret Cho]] as Lt. Klavin\n* [[Edie McClurg]] as Nurse\n* [[Charlie Adler]] as United Express Driver\n* [[Gregg Berger]] as Circus Television Announcer\n* [[Tony Jay]] as Dr. Lipschitz\n\n===Baby singers===\n* [[Lenny Kravitz]]\n* [[Iggy Pop]]\n* [[Lisa Loeb]]\n* [[Gordon Gano]]\n* [[B-Real]] \n* [[Patti Smith]]\n* [[Jakob Dylan]]\n* [[Phife Dawg]]\n* [[Beck]]\n* [[Lou Rawls]]\n* [[Dawn Robinson]]\n* [[Laurie Anderson]]\n* [[Fred Schneider]], [[Kate Pierson]] and [[Cindy Wilson]] of the [[The B-52's]]\n\n==Production==\nThe talks about having ''Rugrats'' making it onto the big screen existed since the beginning of the series. The first attempt was in 1993, when [[Nickelodeon]] made a two-year contract deal with [[20th Century Fox]] to produce new material, but a Nickelodeon executive did not rule out the possibility to make films based on their properties, one of those properties that mentioned was ''[[Rugrats]]'', alongside that the others were ''[[Doug (series)|Doug]]'' and ''[[The Ren & Stimpy Show#Nick-Fox film deal|The Ren & Stimpy Show]]'',<ref name=\"RugratsRotten\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/rugrats_movie/|title=The Rugrats Movie|date=November 20, 1998|work=rottentomatoes.com|accessdate=May 16, 2015}}</ref><ref>https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1350&dat=19930607&id=gldPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=VAMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2074,1837600&hl=en</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1350&dat=19930607&id=gldPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=VAMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2074,1837600&hl=en|title=Toledo Blade \u2013 Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com|access-date=2016-08-13}}</ref> but the contract expired in 1995, with no movies produced (although ''Doug'' eventually got a [[Doug's 1st Movie|theatrical film]] from [[Disney]] in March 1999). In 1994, [[Viacom (original)|Viacom]] acquired [[Paramount Pictures]], and Paramount would distribute the movies instead, development on the movie immediately started a year later after both the acquisition of Paramount and the deal with Fox expired.\n\nTwo months before the release of the movie, an episode prequel titled \"The Family Tree\" was aired as the final episode of [[List of Rugrats episodes#Season 5 (1998)|the fifth season.]] Both the film's beginning and ending parody Paramount and [[Lucasfilm]]'s ''[[Indiana Jones]]'' film series. This later inspired the second segment of the episode \"A Tale of Two Puppies / Okey-Dokey Jones and the Ring of the Sunbeams\", that aired during the [[List of Rugrats episodes#Season 8 (2001-03)|show's eighth season]] on June 1, 2002.\n\nTwo songs were cut from the film during production. The first revolves around Stu and Didi in a nightmare sequence where Dr. Lipschitz criticizes their parenting through a song. The second depicts the Rugrats pushing the Reptar Wagon through the woods, debating what to do about Dil in an army chant style. These two scenes were cut from the theatrical, VHS,  DVD, and Laserdisc releases. However, these scenes are shown on [[CBS]] and [[Nickelodeon]] television airings of the film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bootlegcomparisons.com/2019/03/17/the-rugrats-movie-dvd-vs-cbs-television-broadcast/|title=The Rugrats Movie: DVD Vs. CBS Television Broadcast|last=christophernguyen726|date=2019-03-17|website=Bootleg Comparisons|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-09}}</ref> These scenes were also present in the print novelization.\n\nThe film was released in theaters with a ''[[CatDog]]'' short titled \"''Fetch''\", in which Cat wins a radio contest, and attempts to answer the phone as Dog chases down his tennis ball. This short was later broadcast in ''CatDog'' Episode 21. However, the [[VHS]], [[DVD]] and [[Laserdisc]] release contains a different ''CatDog'' short from Episode 28 titled \"''Winslow's Home Videos''\", in which Winslow shows clips of some of his favorite home videos featuring CatDog's wacky antics.\n\n==Media==\n\n===Home video===\n''The Rugrats Movie'' was released on [[VHS]] and [[DVD]] on March 30, 1999 by [[Paramount Home Entertainment]], which was reprinted many times. Paramount also released the film on [[Laserdisc]]. In 2011, the film was re-released in a three-disc trilogy set alongside its sequels, in honor of ''Rugrats''' 20th anniversary. In addition, it was re-released in some movie sets by Paramount, in 2016 with all the non-sequel Nickelodeon-animated movies up to ''[[Barnyard (film)|Barnyard]]'', as well as a separate 2-disc set with ''[[Hey Arnold!: The Movie]]''.  <ref name=BillboardHomeVideo>{{cite book|last=Goldstein|first=Seth|title=Paramount Preps For 'Rugrats' Vid|url=https://books.google.com/?id=yg0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA7-IA5&dq=%22the+rugrats+movie%22+vhs+march+1999#v=onepage&q=%22the%20rugrats%20movie%22%20vhs%20march%201999|work=Billboard|accessdate=April 9, 2014|page=6|date=January 23, 1999}}</ref><ref name=\"rotten\" />\n\n===Soundtrack===\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Rugrats Movie: Music From the Motion Picture\n| type       = soundtrack\n| artist     = Various Artists\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = November 3, 1998\n| recorded   = 1998\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]], [[Hip hop music|hip hop]], [[Pop music|pop]]\n| length     = 41:51\n| label      = [[Interscope Records|Interscope]], [[Nickelodeon Records|Nickelodeon]]\n| producer   =\n| chronology = Rugrats soundtrack\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Rugrats in Paris: The Movie#Soundtrack|Rugrats in Paris: Music From the Motion Picture]]\n| next_year  = 2000\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = The Rugrats Movie: Music From the Motion Picture\n | type        = soundtrack\n | single1     = [[Take Me There (Blackstreet & M\u00fda song)|Take Me There]]\n | single1date = February 2, 1999\n}}\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{rating|4|5}} [http://www.allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=10:0nfwxq9jldke link]\n| rev2 = [[Entertainment Weekly]]\n| rev2Score = C [http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,273982,00.html link]\n}}\n''The Rugrats Movie: Music From the Motion Picture'' was released on November 3, 1998.<ref name=\"cd\">{{cite web | url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00000DHZX |title=The Rugrats Movie: Music From The Motion Picture [Enhanced CD] [ENHANCED] [SOUNDTRACK] | accessdate=December 25, 2009}}</ref> The enhanced soundtrack contained thirteen tracks, bonus CD-ROM demos and commercials.<ref name=\"cd\"/> [[Amazon.com]]'s Richard Gehr praised the CD for \"[bridging] demographics as nimbly as the [original] show itself [did]\" and for songs \"fans of all ages will love\".<ref name=\"cd\"/>\n\n''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''{{'}}s David Browne rated the ''Music From the Motion Picture'' with a C.<ref name=\"EWcd\">{{cite web | url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,273982,00.html |date=January 8, 1999 |title=The Rugrats Movie: Music From the Motion Picture (1998) |first=David |last=Browne | work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] | accessdate=December 25, 2009}}</ref>\n\nBrowne noted that, while the soundtrack is enjoyable for children and does \"[make] concessions\" for parents, adults may dislike the amount of rap.<ref name=\"EWcd\"/> [[Allmusic]]'s William Ruhlmann reviewed the soundtrack positively, saying \"the result\" of the singers and songs \"is a romp in keeping with the tone of the show and the film\".<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=10:0nfwxq9jldke|title=Rugrats: The Movie Original Soundtrack| website=[[AllMusic]] | accessdate=December 29, 2009}}</ref>\n\n\u2018The Rugrats Movie: Music from the Motion Picture'' spent twenty six weeks on [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], peaking at #19.<ref name=\"billboard\">{{cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/billboard-200#/album/original-soundtrack/rugrats-the-movie/327843|title=Rugrats: The Movie&nbsp;\u2013 Original...| work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard.com]] | accessdate=December 29, 2009}}</ref>\n\nOne song written for the film's soundtrack that was ultimately removed was \"(Safe in This) Sky Life\", a new track by English rock musician [[David Bowie]]; the song marked a reunion with longtime collaborator [[Tony Visconti]], who would go on to produce all of Bowie's material from 2002 up until [[Death of David Bowie|his death in 2016]]. The track would later be re-recorded as a [[B-side]] for Bowie's 2002 single \"[[Everyone Says 'Hi']]\", under the shortened title of \"Safe\".<ref>\"The Complete David Bowie\" by Nicholas Pegg, {{ISBN|1-903111-40-4}} (p.151)</ref>\n\nIn honor of its twentieth anniversary, the film's soundtrack was released on vinyl on November 30, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2018/11/the-rugrats-movie-20th-anniversary-soundtrack-vinyl-release|title='The Rugrats Movie' Soundtrack is Getting a 20th Anniversary Limited Edition Vinyl Release|accessdate=2018-11-28|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]}}</ref>\n\n===Track listing===\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Artist(s)\n| total_length = 41:51\n| title1 = [[Take Me There (Blackstreet & M\u00fda song)|Take Me There]]\n| length1 = 5:04\n| extra1 = [[Blackstreet]] & [[M\u00fda]] featuring [[Mase]] & [[Blinky Blink]]\n| title2 = I Throw My Toys Around\n| length2 = 3:02\n| extra2 = [[No Doubt]] featuring [[Elvis Costello]]\n| title3 = This World Is Something New to Me\n| extra3 = [[Dawn Robinson]], [[Lisa Loeb]], [[B-Real]], [[Patti Smith]], [[Lou Rawls]], [[Laurie Anderson]], [[Gordon Gano]], [[Fred Schneider]], [[Kate Pierson]], [[Cindy Wilson]], [[Phife Dawg]], [[Lenny Kravitz]], [[Beck]], [[Jakob Dylan]] and [[Iggy Pop]]\n| length3 = 1:59\n| title4 = All Day\n| extra4 = Lisa Loeb\n| length4 = 3:30\n| title5 = Dil-A-Bye\n| extra5 = [[Elizabeth Daily|E.G. Daily]]\n| length5 = 3:43\n| title6 = A Baby is a Gift from a Bob\n| extra6 = [[Cree Summer]] & [[Cheryl Chase (actress)|Cheryl Chase]]\n| length6 = 1:57\n| title7 = [[One Way or Another]]\n| extra7 = Chase\n| length7 = 3:17\n| title8 = Wild Ride\n| extra8 = Kevi featuring Lisa Stone\n| length8 = 2:43\n| title9 = On Your Marks, Get Set, Ready, Go!\n| extra9 = [[Busta Rhymes]]\n| length9 = 3:41\n| title10 = [[Witch Doctor (song)|Witch Doctor]]\n| extra10 = [[Devo]]\n| length10 = 3:33\n| title11 = Take the Train\n| extra11 = [[Rakim]] and [[Danny Saber]]\n| length11 = 4:05\n| title12 = Yo Ho Ho and a Bottle of Yum\n| extra12 = E.G. Daily, [[Christine Cavanaugh]] & [[Kath Soucie]]\n| length12 = 2:18\n| all_writing = \n}}\n\n===Video games===\nVideo games were released for [[Game Boy]] and [[Game Boy Color]] titled ''[[The Rugrats Movie (video game)|The Rugrats Movie]]'' and ''Rugrats: The Movie'' respectively, with the former being released on June 19, 1998<ref name=\"gameboy\">{{cite web | url=http://gameboy.ign.com/objects/491/491563.html |title=The Rubrats Movie |first= |last= | website=[[IGN]] | accessdate=December 22, 2009}}</ref> and the latter on March 12, 1999.<ref name=\"color\">{{cite web | url=http://gameboy.ign.com/objects/011/011858.html |date= |title=Rugrats: The Movie | website=[[IGN]] | accessdate=December 22, 2009}}</ref> Both games were developed by Software Creations (US) and released by [[THQ]].<ref name=\"color\"/><ref name=\"gamerank\"/> They were [[side-scrolling video game]]s and featured 8 levels, with the plot revolving around finding a replacement for Dil after he disappears.<ref name=\"moby\">{{cite web | url=http://www.mobygames.com/game/rugrats-movie |date= |title=The Rugrats Movie| website=[[MobyGames]]| accessdate=December 24, 2009}}</ref> [[IGN]]'s Peer Schneider graded the Game Boy Color game with an overall score of 5 out of 10.<ref name=\"colorreview\">{{cite web | url=http://gameboy.ign.com/articles/161/161858p1.html |date= |title=Rugrats: The Movie |first=Peer |last=Schneider | website=[[IGN]] | accessdate=December 22, 2009}}</ref>\n\nSchneider states that the game doesn't have much \"to hold the attention of older gamers\", but that \"kids will love the easy gameplay, recognizable characters and memorable Rugrats tunes\". He closes with saying that \"unless you're looking for something to entertain and challenge at the same time, parents can't go wrong in buying the game for their kids.\"<ref name=\"colorreview\"/> Writing for [[GameSpot]], Cameron Davis gave the ''Rugrats: The Movie'' a mixed review, stating that it wasn't \"groundbreaking or innovative\", but that the game \"does what it sets out to do well\".<ref name=\"gamespot\">{{cite web | url=http://www.gamespot.com/gbc/action/rugratsthemovie/review.html |date= |title=Rugrats: The Movie Review |first=Cameron |last=Davis | website=[[GameSpot]] | accessdate=December 24, 2009}}</ref>\n\nDavis noted that the game was aimed at children and praised the \"difficulty level\" as being \"set just right\", so that \"younger players can explore the levels in comfort thanks to the good collision detection and responsive controls, while those with a bit more Game Boy experience can use the generous time limits to ferret out hidden objects\". The game overall was given a 6.2 by the critic.<ref name=\"gamespot\"/> On aggregator site [[GameRankings]], ''The Rugrats Movie'' is rated as a 55%<ref name=\"gamerank\">{{cite web | url=http://www.gamerankings.com/gameboy/562858-the-rugrats-movie/index.html |date= |title=The Rugrats Movie| website=[[GameRankings]] | accessdate=December 24, 2009}}</ref> while ''Rugrats: The Movie'' earned a 61.75%.<ref name=\"gamerank2\">{{cite web | url=http://www.gamerankings.com/gbc/198523-rugrats-the-movie/index.html |date= |title=Rugrats: The Movie| website=[[GameRankings]]| accessdate=December 24, 2009}}</ref>\n\nA [[PC game|computer game]] inspired by the film entitled ''The Rugrats Movie: Activity Challenge'' was developed and published by [[Br\u00f8derbund]] and released on September 14, 1998. It features six games and a bonus level that can be attained if a certain item is obtained in a game.<ref name=\"activity\">{{cite web | url=http://www.mobygames.com/game/windows/rugrats-movie-activity-challenge |date= |title=The Rugrats Movie: Activity Challenge| publisher=[[MobyGames]]| accessdate=December 24, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Books===\nSeveral books were released by [[Simon & Schuster]]'s Simon Spotlight branch and [[Nickelodeon]] inspired by ''The Rugrats Movie''. ''Tommy's New Playmate'' and ''The Rugrats Versus the Monkeys'' were also released on October 1, 1998, authored by Luke David and illustrated by John Kurtz and Sandrina Kurtz.<ref name=\"playmate\">{{cite book |title=The Rugrats Movie Tommys New Playmate (The Rugrats Movie 8 X 8) (Paperback) |isbn=0689821417 |url=https://archive.org/details/tommysnewplaymat00davi |last1=David |first1=Luke |year=1998 }}</ref><ref name=\"monkeys\">{{cite book |title=The Rugrats Movie: The Rugrats Versus the Monkeys (The Rugrats Movie 8 X 8) (Paperback) |isbn=0689821425 |url=https://archive.org/details/rugratsversusmon00davi |last1=David |first1=Luke |year=1998 }}</ref>\n\n''The Rugrats Movie Storybook'', released on the same date and using the same illustrators and publishers, was written by Sarah Wilson.<ref name=\"wilson\">{{cite book |title=The Rugrats Movie Storybook (Paperback) |isbn=068982128X |url=https://archive.org/details/rugratsmoviestor00will |last1=Willson |first1=Sarah |year=1998 }}</ref> The same date saw the release of ''The Rugrats Movie: Hang On To Your Diapies, Babies, We're Going In!: Trivia from the Hit Movie!'', a trivia book written by Kitty Richards.<ref name=\"trvia\">{{cite book |title=Rugrats Movie, The: Hang On To Your Diapies, Babies, We're Going In!: Trivia from the Hit Movie! (Paperback) |isbn=0689822766 |url=https://archive.org/details/hangontoyourdiap00rich |last1=Richards |first1=Kitty |year=1998 }}</ref>\n\nA novelization of the film written by Cathy East Dubowski was published on October 1, 1998, by Tandem Library.<ref name=\"tandem\">{{cite book |date= |title=Rugrats Movie (Hardcover) |isbn=0613872681}}</ref> The following month, a 144-page guidebook, ''The Making of The Rugrats Movie: Behind the Scenes at Klasky Csupo'', was released on November 1, 1998, by MSG.<ref>{{cite book|title=The making of the Rugrats movie : behind the scenes at Klasky Csupo|work=worldcat.org|oclc = 040590978}}</ref> In May 1999, [[Hal Leonard Corporation|Hal Leonard Publishing Corporation]] released a book titled ''The Rugrats Movie''.<ref name=\"leonard\">{{cite book |date= May 1999|title=The Rugrats Movie (Paperback) |isbn=0634005146}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\nThe film was released on November 20, 1998, and made [[United States dollar|US$]]27,321,470 in its opening weekend,<ref name=\"mojo\">{{cite web | url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=rugratsmovie.htm |date= |title=THE RUGRATS MOVIE |first= |last= | website=Box Office Mojo | accessdate=December 22, 2009}}</ref> from 2,782 theaters, averaging about $9,821 per venue and ranking as the #1 movie that weekend, beating out ''[[Enemy of the State (film)|Enemy of the State]]''.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/12/28/business/prince-of-egypt-is-no-king-at-the-box-office.html?scp=4&sq=The%20Rugrats%20Movie&st=cse |date=December 28, 1998 |title='Prince of Egypt' Is No King at the Box-Office |first=Geraldine |last=FABRIKANT | work=[[The New York Times]] | accessdate=December 24, 2009}}</ref> In total, ''The Rugrats Movie'' made US$140,894,675, $100,494,675 from the domestic market, and $40,400,000 from its foreign release.<ref name=\"mojo\"/>\n\nThe film was released in the [[United Kingdom]] on March 26, 1999, and topped the country's box office for the next three weekends, before being dethroned by ''[[The Faculty (film)|The Faculty]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.25thframe.co.uk/charts/chart.php?chart=19990326|title=Weekend box office 26th March 1999 - 28th March 1999|publisher=www.25thframe.co.uk|accessdate=22 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.25thframe.co.uk/charts/chart.php?chart=19990326|title=Weekend box office 2nd April 1999 - 4th April 1999|publisher=www.25thframe.co.uk|accessdate=22 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.25thframe.co.uk/charts/chart.php?chart=19990326|title=Weekend box office 9th April 1999 - 11th April 1999|publisher=www.25thframe.co.uk|accessdate=22 January 2017}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite news|title= Weekend Box Office : 'Rugrats' Has Kid Power |work= The Los Angeles Times|date=November 24, 1998|url= http://articles.latimes.com/1998/nov/24/entertainment/ca-47071|accessdate=November 10, 2010|first=Robert W.|last=Welkos}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\n''The Rugrats Movie'' holds a 59% rating on the review aggregator website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 50 reviews (30 positive and 21 negative), with an average rating of 5.8/10. The consensus is: \"Charming characters; loads of fun for kids and adults.\"<ref name=\"rotten\">{{cite web | url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/rugrats_movie/ |date= |title=The Rugrats Movie (1998) |first= |last= | website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] | accessdate=December 22, 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] gave the film 2 stars out of 4.<ref name=\"ebert\">{{cite news | url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19981120/REVIEWS/811200306/1023 |date= |title=The Rugrats Movie (G) |first=Roger |last=Ebert | work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] | accessdate=December 24, 2009}}</ref> Ebert wrote that the film's target audience was primarily younger children, and that, while he as an adult disliked it, he \"might have\" liked it if he were younger and would recommend it for children.<ref name=\"ebert\"/> ''[[The New York Times]]''{{'}}s Anita Gates reviewed ''The Rugrats Movie'' positively, calling it a \"delight\".<ref name=\"nyreview\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/11/20/movies/film-review-a-sibling-takes-a-new-rival-for-a-ride.html?scp=20&sq=The%20Rugrats%20Movie&st=cse |date=November 20, 1998 |title=FILM REVIEW; A Sibling Takes a New Rival for a Ride |first=Anita |last=Gates | work=[[The New York Times]] | accessdate=December 24, 2009}}</ref>\n\nLisa Schwarzbaum of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' graded the film with a B.<ref name=\"EW\">{{cite web | url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,285889,00.html |date=November 27, 1998 |title=The Rugrats Movie (1998) |first=Lisa |last=Schwarzbaum | work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] | accessdate=December 24, 2009}}</ref> Schwarzbaum praised the movie for its appeal to both adult and child audiences, \"juxtaposing the blithely self-absorbed parallel universes of small, diapered children and their large, Dockered parents\".<ref name=\"EW\"/> However, other ''Entertainment Weekly'' reviewer Ty Burr gave ''The Rugrats Movie'' a B\u2212, criticizing that the film's issues sprung from it being \"bigger\" than the original series, thus it having more cultural references, out-of-place CGI scenes, and \"[going] into scary territory\".<ref name=\"EW2\">{{cite web | url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,272906,00.html |date=April 2, 1999 |title=The Rugrats Movie (1999) |first=Ty |last=Burr | work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] | accessdate=December 24, 2009}}</ref> Despite these faults, Burr did praise the \"escaped circus monkeys\" for being \"scary in a good way\", as well as a joke that was accessible to younger audiences.<ref name=\"EW2\"/>\n\n==Sequels==\nTwo sequels have been released: ''[[Rugrats in Paris: The Movie]]'', which was released on November 17, 2000, and ''[[Rugrats Go Wild]]'', which was released on June 13, 2003.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{AllMovie title}}\n*{{BCDB title}}\n* {{mojo title|rugratsmovie}}\n*{{IMDb title}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|rugrats_movie}}\n*{{TCMDb title}}\n\n{{Nickelodeon Movies}}\n{{Rugrats}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rugrats Movie, The}}\n[[Category:1998 films]]\n[[Category:1998 animated films]]\n[[Category:1990s adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:1990s American animated films]]\n[[Category:American adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy films]]\n[[Category:American musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Animated adventure films]]\n[[Category:Animated comedy films]]\n[[Category:Animated musical films]]\n[[Category:Animated films based on animated series]]\n[[Category:Directorial debut films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Mark Mothersbaugh]]\n[[Category:Films about missing people]]\n[[Category:Klasky Csupo animated films]]\n[[Category:Nickelodeon animated films]]\n[[Category:Nickelodeon Movies films]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures animated films]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Rugrats and All Grown Up!]]\n[[Category:Rugrats (film series)]]\n[[Category:Films set in forests]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by David N. Weiss]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the movie|the video game|The Rugrats Movie (video game)}}\n{{Use American English|date = March 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Rugrats Movie\n| image          = File:This_is_the_Theatrical_Release_Poster_of_the_Rugrats_Movie.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| directors      = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Igor Kovalyov]]\n* Norton Virgien\n}}\n| producers      = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Arlene Klasky]]\n* [[G\u00e1bor Csup\u00f3]]\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* [[David N. Weiss]]\n* J. David Stem\n}}\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[Rugrats]]''|Arlene Klasky<br />Gabor Csupo<br />[[Paul Germain]]}}\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n* [[E. G. Daily]]\n* [[Tara Strong]]\n* [[Christine Cavanaugh]]\n* [[Kath Soucie]]\n* [[Cheryl Chase (actress)|Cheryl Chase]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Mark Mothersbaugh]]<ref name=AFIRugrats>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/DetailView.aspx?s=&Movie=61550|title=Detail view of Movies Page|work=afi.com|accessdate=May 16, 2015}}</ref>\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* John Bryant\n* Kimberly Rettberg\n}}\n| production companies = [[Klasky Csupo]]<ref name=AFIRugrats/>\n| distributor    = {{plainlist|\n* [[Paramount Pictures]]<ref name=AFIRugrats/>\n* [[Nickelodeon Movies]]<ref name=AFIRugrats/>\n}}\n| released       = {{Film date|1998|11|20}}\n| runtime        = 80 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 80:02--><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/rugrats-movie-1970-3 | title=''The Rugrats Movie'' (U) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=December 16, 1998 | accessdate=August 28, 2016}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $24 million\n| gross          = $140.9 million\n}}\n'''''The Rugrats Movie''''' is a 1998 American [[Animation|animated]] [[adventure]] [[comedy film]] based on the [[Nickelodeon]]\nanimated television series ''[[Rugrats]]''. It was directed by [[Igor Kovalyov]] and Norton Virgien and written by [[David N. Weiss]] & J. David Stem.<ref name=\"The Rugrats Movie\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/443844/Rugrats-Movie-The/full-credits.html|title=The Rugrats Movie|work=[[Turner Classic Movies]]|publisher=[[Turner Broadcasting System]] ([[Time Warner]])|location=[[Atlanta]]|accessdate=November 10, 2016}}</ref> The film introduced [[Tommy Pickles]]' baby brother [[Dil Pickles]], who appeared on the original series the next year. The film features the voices of [[E. G. Daily]], [[Tara Strong]], [[Christine Cavanaugh]], [[Kath Soucie]], [[Cheryl Chase (actress)|Cheryl Chase]], [[Cree Summer]], and [[Charlie Adler]], along with guest stars [[David Spade]], [[Whoopi Goldberg]], [[Margaret Cho]], [[Busta Rhymes]], and [[Tim Curry]]. The events of the film take place before the [[List of Rugrats episodes|sixth season]] of ''Rugrats''.\n\nPlans for a Rugrats film adaptation, along with [[Ren and Stimpy]] and [[Doug (series)|Doug]], began when Nickelodeon made a contract with [[20th Century Fox]] to produce films between 1993 and 1995.<ref name=\":0\" /> However, the contract expired with no films into production. Around the same year when contract expired, development of the film restarted with [[Paramount Pictures]] since Nick's parent company, [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]], purchased the studio in 1994. \n\nThe film holds the distinction for being the first animated film from [[Nickelodeon Movies]], as well as the first to be based on a Nicktoon. Paramount Pictures originally released it in the United States on November 20, 1998.<ref name=AFIRugrats/> The film received mixed to positive reviews from critics and grossed $141 million worldwide.\n\n==Plot==\n[[Didi Pickles]] is [[pregnancy|pregnant]] with her second baby, which she believes will be a girl while everyone else believes it will be a boy. Didi goes into labor during her baby shower and her friends rush her to the hospital. While this is happening, the kids crawl off and explore a nursery area before being found by the other parents. When the baby is finally born after a montage of [[Reincarnation|past lives]], it turns out to a boy and they name him [[Dil Pickles|Dil]].\n\nDil quickly becomes a very spoiled and mean baby, crying non-stop for attention, not listening to his mom and dad, keeping all of the toys for himself, and refusing to share with [[Tommy Pickles|Tommy]]. After a nasty fight between Tommy and Dil over Tommy's teddy bear, their father, [[Stu Pickles|Stu]] has a conversation with him about being a big brother and the responsibility he now has, assuring him that one day he will be happy to have Dil as his little brother. He also gives Tommy a locket with a picture of Tommy and Dil taped together and a watch inside, which he calls his \"sponsitility\" (his term for responsibility).\n\nWhen Dil pushes the other babies too far, they decide to take him back to the hospital despite Tommy's disapproval, and end up driving recklessly through the streets in a [[Reptar]] Wagon which Stu had built for a contest. Along the way, Dil secretly steals [[Angelica Pickles|Angelica's]] Cynthia doll, which prompts her to take the family dog, [[List of Rugrats characters|Spike]] and they embark on a quest to find the babies and retrieve Cynthia.\n\nThe babies eventually crash in the woods, where they realize that they are lost. They spot a ranger's cabin where they believe a \"lizard\" (a mispronunciation of [[wizard (fantasy)|wizard]]) lives, and decide to go there, believing that it can take them home. After an encounter with a gang of runaway circus monkeys, Dil is taken away by them. Tommy vows to find Dil by himself, after [[Chuckie Finster|Chuckie]], [[Phil and Lil]] agree they are better off without him.\n\nMeanwhile, the parents find out that the babies are missing and try to find them. However, it becomes a media sensation with numerous news reporters constantly asking the adults questions and intentionally enrages Stu's brother [[Drew Pickles|Drew]] into attacking Stu by telling him he lost Angelica.\n\nTommy eventually finds Dil during a storm, and are forced to take shelter under a tree. But as Tommy tries to take care of him, Dil selfishly drinks all of the milk and keeps the large blanket for himself, which leads to the blanket tearing in half and Tommy falling into a puddle of mud. Tommy finally snaps and nearly pours banana baby food on Dil for the monkeys to take him away, but Tommy's rage and the storm's lightning and thunder scare Dil so much that he sees the error of his ways. They reconcile and sleep peacefully.\n\nAfter the storm, the other babies find Tommy and Dil, and after running into Angelica and Spike they make their way to the \"lizard\". While on a bridge, they are confronted by the monkeys, but are then scared off by a [[wolf]] who's been hunting down the babies since they arrived in the woods. Spike intervenes and fights the wolf until they both fall from the bridge. Meanwhile, Stu, who has been looking for the babies via a [[pterodactyl]]-like aircraft he made, finally finds them, but crash lands into the ranger's cabin. Believing he is the \"lizard,\" the babies wish for Spike back instead of going home. Stu falls through the bridge and finds Spike, who actually survived the fall by landing on a strut of the bridge. The babies are then reunited with their families, and the monkeys with their circus owners. The monkeys attack Rex Pester, the most obnoxious of all the news reporters, much to Betty and Charlotte's amusement. Dil finally learns to share when he drinks half of a bottle of formula and gives the other half to Tommy. The families return home and the babies accept Dil as one of the group after he assists them in getting an ice cream sundae form the top shelf of the refrigerator.\n\nIn a [[post-credits scene]], Grandpa Lou is sleeping in the Reptar Wagon when Grandpa Boris' goat kicks it, sending both the wagon and Grandpa down the street and presumably starting another adventure all over again.\n\n==Cast==\n{{main article|List of Rugrats characters}}\n===Main===\n* [[E. G. Daily]] as [[Tommy Pickles]]\n* [[Tara Strong]] as Dil Pickles\n* [[Christine Cavanaugh]] as Chuckie Finster\n* [[Kath Soucie]] as Phil, Lil, and Betty DeVille\n* [[Cheryl Chase (actress)|Cheryl Chase]] as [[Angelica Pickles]]\n* [[Cree Summer]] as Susie Carmichael\n\n===Supporting===\n* [[Jack Riley (actor)|Jack Riley]] as Stu Pickles\n* [[Joe Alaskey]] as Grandpa Lou Pickles\n* [[Melanie Chartoff]] as Didi Pickles and Grandma Minka\n* [[Michael Bell (actor)|Michael Bell]] as Drew Pickles, Chas<!--Closing credits list the character as Chas, not Chaz--> Finster and Grandpa Boris\n* [[Tress MacNeille]] as Charlotte Pickles\n* [[Philip Proctor|Phil Proctor]] as Howard DeVille\n\n===Guest===\n* [[David Spade]] as Ranger Frank\n* [[Whoopi Goldberg]] as Ranger Margaret\n* [[Tim Curry]] as Rex Pester\n* [[Hattie Winston]] as Dr. Lucy Carmichael\n* [[Andrea Martin]] as Aunt Miriam\n* [[Busta Rhymes]] as Reptar Wagon\n* [[Roger Clinton, Jr.]] as Air Crewman\n* [[Margaret Cho]] as Lt. Klavin\n* [[Edie McClurg]] as Nurse\n* [[Charlie Adler]] as United Express Driver\n* [[Gregg Berger]] as Circus Television Announcer\n* [[Tony Jay]] as Dr. Lipschitz\n\n===Baby singers===\n* [[Lenny Kravitz]]\n* [[Iggy Pop]]\n* [[Lisa Loeb]]\n* [[Gordon Gano]]\n* [[B-Real]] \n* [[Patti Smith]]\n* [[Jakob Dylan]]\n* [[Phife Dawg]]\n* [[Beck]]\n* [[Lou Rawls]]\n* [[Dawn Robinson]]\n* [[Laurie Anderson]]\n* [[Fred Schneider]], [[Kate Pierson]] and [[Cindy Wilson]] of the [[The B-52's]]\n\n==Production==\nThe talks about having ''Rugrats'' making it onto the big screen existed since the beginning of the series. The first attempt was in 1993, when [[Nickelodeon]] made a two-year contract deal with [[20th Century Fox]] to produce new material, but a Nickelodeon executive did not rule out the possibility to make films based on their properties, one of those properties that mentioned was ''[[Rugrats]]'', alongside that the others were ''[[Doug (series)|Doug]]'' and ''[[The Ren & Stimpy Show#Nick-Fox film deal|The Ren & Stimpy Show]]'',<ref name=\"RugratsRotten\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/rugrats_movie/|title=The Rugrats Movie|date=November 20, 1998|work=rottentomatoes.com|accessdate=May 16, 2015}}</ref><ref>https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1350&dat=19930607&id=gldPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=VAMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2074,1837600&hl=en</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1350&dat=19930607&id=gldPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=VAMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2074,1837600&hl=en|title=Toledo Blade \u2013 Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com|access-date=2016-08-13}}</ref> but the contract expired in 1995, with no movies produced (although ''Doug'' eventually got a [[Doug's 1st Movie|theatrical film]] from [[Disney]] in March 1999). In 1994, [[Viacom (original)|Viacom]] acquired [[Paramount Pictures]], and Paramount would distribute the movies instead, development on the movie immediately started a year later after both the acquisition of Paramount and the deal with Fox expired.\n\nTwo months before the release of the movie, an episode prequel titled \"The Family Tree\" was aired as the final episode of [[List of Rugrats episodes#Season 5 (1998)|the fifth season.]] Both the film's beginning and ending parody Paramount and [[Lucasfilm]]'s ''[[Indiana Jones]]'' film series. This later inspired the second segment of the episode \"A Tale of Two Puppies / Okey-Dokey Jones and the Ring of the Sunbeams\", that aired during the [[List of Rugrats episodes#Season 8 (2001-03)|show's eighth season]] on June 1, 2002.\n\nTwo songs were cut from the film during production. The first revolves around Stu and Didi in a nightmare sequence where Dr. Lipschitz criticizes their parenting through a song. The second depicts the Rugrats pushing the Reptar Wagon through the woods, debating what to do about Dil in an army chant style. These two scenes were cut from the theatrical, VHS,  DVD, and Laserdisc releases. However, these scenes are shown on [[CBS]] and [[Nickelodeon]] television airings of the film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bootlegcomparisons.com/2019/03/17/the-rugrats-movie-dvd-vs-cbs-television-broadcast/|title=The Rugrats Movie: DVD Vs. CBS Television Broadcast|last=christophernguyen726|date=2019-03-17|website=Bootleg Comparisons|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-09}}</ref> These scenes were also present in the print novelization.\n\nThe film was released in theaters with a ''[[CatDog]]'' short titled \"''Fetch''\", in which Cat wins a radio contest, and attempts to answer the phone as Dog chases down his tennis ball. This short was later broadcast in ''CatDog'' Episode 21. However, the [[VHS]], [[DVD]] and [[Laserdisc]] release contains a different ''CatDog'' short from Episode 28 titled \"''Winslow's Home Videos''\", in which Winslow shows clips of some of his favorite home videos featuring CatDog's wacky antics.\n\n==Media==\n\n===Home video===\n''The Rugrats Movie'' was released on [[VHS]] and [[DVD]] on March 30, 1999 by [[Paramount Home Entertainment]], which was reprinted many times. Paramount also released the film on [[Laserdisc]]. In 2011, the film was re-released in a three-disc trilogy set alongside its sequels, in honor of ''Rugrats''' 20th anniversary. In addition, it was re-released in some movie sets by Paramount, in 2016 with all the non-sequel Nickelodeon-animated movies up to ''[[Barnyard (film)|Barnyard]]'', as well as a separate 2-disc set with ''[[Hey Arnold!: The Movie]]''.  <ref name=BillboardHomeVideo>{{cite book|last=Goldstein|first=Seth|title=Paramount Preps For 'Rugrats' Vid|url=https://books.google.com/?id=yg0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA7-IA5&dq=%22the+rugrats+movie%22+vhs+march+1999#v=onepage&q=%22the%20rugrats%20movie%22%20vhs%20march%201999|work=Billboard|accessdate=April 9, 2014|page=6|date=January 23, 1999}}</ref><ref name=\"rotten\" />\n\n===Soundtrack===\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Rugrats Movie: Music From the Motion Picture\n| type       = soundtrack\n| artist     = Various Artists\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = November 3, 1998\n| recorded   = 1998\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]], [[Hip hop music|hip hop]], [[Pop music|pop]]\n| length     = 41:51\n| label      = [[Interscope Records|Interscope]], [[Nickelodeon Records|Nickelodeon]]\n| producer   =\n| chronology = Rugrats soundtrack\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Rugrats in Paris: The Movie#Soundtrack|Rugrats in Paris: Music From the Motion Picture]]\n| next_year  = 2000\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = The Rugrats Movie: Music From the Motion Picture\n | type        = soundtrack\n | single1     = [[Take Me There (Blackstreet & M\u00fda song)|Take Me There]]\n | single1date = February 2, 1999\n}}\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{rating|4|5}} [http://www.allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=10:0nfwxq9jldke link]\n| rev2 = [[Entertainment Weekly]]\n| rev2Score = C [http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,273982,00.html link]\n}}\n''The Rugrats Movie: Music From the Motion Picture'' was released on November 3, 1998.<ref name=\"cd\">{{cite web | url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00000DHZX |title=The Rugrats Movie: Music From The Motion Picture [Enhanced CD] [ENHANCED] [SOUNDTRACK] | accessdate=December 25, 2009}}</ref> The enhanced soundtrack contained thirteen tracks, bonus CD-ROM demos and commercials.<ref name=\"cd\"/> [[Amazon.com]]'s Richard Gehr praised the CD for \"[bridging] demographics as nimbly as the [original] show itself [did]\" and for songs \"fans of all ages will love\".<ref name=\"cd\"/>\n\n''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''{{'}}s David Browne rated the ''Music From the Motion Picture'' with a C.<ref name=\"EWcd\">{{cite web | url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,273982,00.html |date=January 8, 1999 |title=The Rugrats Movie: Music From the Motion Picture (1998) |first=David |last=Browne | work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] | accessdate=December 25, 2009}}</ref>\n\nBrowne noted that, while the soundtrack is enjoyable for children and does \"[make] concessions\" for parents, adults may dislike the amount of rap.<ref name=\"EWcd\"/> [[Allmusic]]'s William Ruhlmann reviewed the soundtrack positively, saying \"the result\" of the singers and songs \"is a romp in keeping with the tone of the show and the film\".<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=10:0nfwxq9jldke|title=Rugrats: The Movie Original Soundtrack| website=[[AllMusic]] | accessdate=December 29, 2009}}</ref>\n\n\u2018The Rugrats Movie: Music from the Motion Picture'' spent twenty six weeks on [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], peaking at #19.<ref name=\"billboard\">{{cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/billboard-200#/album/original-soundtrack/rugrats-the-movie/327843|title=Rugrats: The Movie&nbsp;\u2013 Original...| work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard.com]] | accessdate=December 29, 2009}}</ref>\n\nOne song written for the film's soundtrack that was ultimately removed was \"(Safe in This) Sky Life\", a new track by English rock musician [[David Bowie]]; the song marked a reunion with longtime collaborator [[Tony Visconti]], who would go on to produce all of Bowie's material from 2002 up until [[Death of David Bowie|his death in 2016]]. The track would later be re-recorded as a [[B-side]] for Bowie's 2002 single \"[[Everyone Says 'Hi']]\", under the shortened title of \"Safe\".<ref>\"The Complete David Bowie\" by Nicholas Pegg, {{ISBN|1-903111-40-4}} (p.151)</ref>\n\nIn honor of its twentieth anniversary, the film's soundtrack was released on vinyl on November 30, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2018/11/the-rugrats-movie-20th-anniversary-soundtrack-vinyl-release|title='The Rugrats Movie' Soundtrack is Getting a 20th Anniversary Limited Edition Vinyl Release|accessdate=2018-11-28|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]}}</ref>\n\n===Track listing===\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Artist(s)\n| total_length = 41:51\n| title1 = [[Take Me There (Blackstreet & M\u00fda song)|Take Me There]]\n| length1 = 5:04\n| extra1 = [[Blackstreet]] & [[M\u00fda]] featuring [[Mase]] & [[Blinky Blink]]\n| title2 = I Throw My Toys Around\n| length2 = 3:02\n| extra2 = [[No Doubt]] featuring [[Elvis Costello]]\n| title3 = This World Is Something New to Me\n| extra3 = [[Dawn Robinson]], [[Lisa Loeb]], [[B-Real]], [[Patti Smith]], [[Lou Rawls]], [[Laurie Anderson]], [[Gordon Gano]], [[Fred Schneider]], [[Kate Pierson]], [[Cindy Wilson]], [[Phife Dawg]], [[Lenny Kravitz]], [[Beck]], [[Jakob Dylan]] and [[Iggy Pop]]\n| length3 = 1:59\n| title4 = All Day\n| extra4 = Lisa Loeb\n| length4 = 3:30\n| title5 = Dil-A-Bye\n| extra5 = [[Elizabeth Daily|E.G. Daily]]\n| length5 = 3:43\n| title6 = A Baby is a Gift from a Bob\n| extra6 = [[Cree Summer]] & [[Cheryl Chase (actress)|Cheryl Chase]]\n| length6 = 1:57\n| title7 = [[One Way or Another]]\n| extra7 = Chase\n| length7 = 3:17\n| title8 = Wild Ride\n| extra8 = Kevi featuring Lisa Stone\n| length8 = 2:43\n| title9 = On Your Marks, Get Set, Ready, Go!\n| extra9 = [[Busta Rhymes]]\n| length9 = 3:41\n| title10 = [[Witch Doctor (song)|Witch Doctor]]\n| extra10 = [[Devo]]\n| length10 = 3:33\n| title11 = Take the Train\n| extra11 = [[Rakim]] and [[Danny Saber]]\n| length11 = 4:05\n| title12 = Yo Ho Ho and a Bottle of Yum\n| extra12 = E.G. Daily, [[Christine Cavanaugh]] & [[Kath Soucie]]\n| length12 = 2:18\n| all_writing = \n}}\n\n===Video games===\nVideo games were released for [[Game Boy]] and [[Game Boy Color]] titled ''[[The Rugrats Movie (video game)|The Rugrats Movie]]'' and ''Rugrats: The Movie'' respectively, with the former being released on June 19, 1998<ref name=\"gameboy\">{{cite web | url=http://gameboy.ign.com/objects/491/491563.html |title=The Rubrats Movie |first= |last= | website=[[IGN]] | accessdate=December 22, 2009}}</ref> and the latter on March 12, 1999.<ref name=\"color\">{{cite web | url=http://gameboy.ign.com/objects/011/011858.html |date= |title=Rugrats: The Movie | website=[[IGN]] | accessdate=December 22, 2009}}</ref> Both games were developed by Software Creations (US) and released by [[THQ]].<ref name=\"color\"/><ref name=\"gamerank\"/> They were [[side-scrolling video game]]s and featured 8 levels, with the plot revolving around finding a replacement for Dil after he disappears.<ref name=\"moby\">{{cite web | url=http://www.mobygames.com/game/rugrats-movie |date= |title=The Rugrats Movie| website=[[MobyGames]]| accessdate=December 24, 2009}}</ref> [[IGN]]'s Peer Schneider graded the Game Boy Color game with an overall score of 5 out of 10.<ref name=\"colorreview\">{{cite web | url=http://gameboy.ign.com/articles/161/161858p1.html |date= |title=Rugrats: The Movie |first=Peer |last=Schneider | website=[[IGN]] | accessdate=December 22, 2009}}</ref>\n\nSchneider states that the game doesn't have much \"to hold the attention of older gamers\", but that \"kids will love the easy gameplay, recognizable characters and memorable Rugrats tunes\". He closes with saying that \"unless you're looking for something to entertain and challenge at the same time, parents can't go wrong in buying the game for their kids.\"<ref name=\"colorreview\"/> Writing for [[GameSpot]], Cameron Davis gave the ''Rugrats: The Movie'' a mixed review, stating that it wasn't \"groundbreaking or innovative\", but that the game \"does what it sets out to do well\".<ref name=\"gamespot\">{{cite web | url=http://www.gamespot.com/gbc/action/rugratsthemovie/review.html |date= |title=Rugrats: The Movie Review |first=Cameron |last=Davis | website=[[GameSpot]] | accessdate=December 24, 2009}}</ref>\n\nDavis noted that the game was aimed at children and praised the \"difficulty level\" as being \"set just right\", so that \"younger players can explore the levels in comfort thanks to the good collision detection and responsive controls, while those with a bit more Game Boy experience can use the generous time limits to ferret out hidden objects\". The game overall was given a 6.2 by the critic.<ref name=\"gamespot\"/> On aggregator site [[GameRankings]], ''The Rugrats Movie'' is rated as a 55%<ref name=\"gamerank\">{{cite web | url=http://www.gamerankings.com/gameboy/562858-the-rugrats-movie/index.html |date= |title=The Rugrats Movie| website=[[GameRankings]] | accessdate=December 24, 2009}}</ref> while ''Rugrats: The Movie'' earned a 61.75%.<ref name=\"gamerank2\">{{cite web | url=http://www.gamerankings.com/gbc/198523-rugrats-the-movie/index.html |date= |title=Rugrats: The Movie| website=[[GameRankings]]| accessdate=December 24, 2009}}</ref>\n\nA [[PC game|computer game]] inspired by the film entitled ''The Rugrats Movie: Activity Challenge'' was developed and published by [[Br\u00f8derbund]] and released on September 14, 1998. It features six games and a bonus level that can be attained if a certain item is obtained in a game.<ref name=\"activity\">{{cite web | url=http://www.mobygames.com/game/windows/rugrats-movie-activity-challenge |date= |title=The Rugrats Movie: Activity Challenge| publisher=[[MobyGames]]| accessdate=December 24, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Books===\nSeveral books were released by [[Simon & Schuster]]'s Simon Spotlight branch and [[Nickelodeon]] inspired by ''The Rugrats Movie''. ''Tommy's New Playmate'' and ''The Rugrats Versus the Monkeys'' were also released on October 1, 1998, authored by Luke David and illustrated by John Kurtz and Sandrina Kurtz.<ref name=\"playmate\">{{cite book |title=The Rugrats Movie Tommys New Playmate (The Rugrats Movie 8 X 8) (Paperback) |isbn=0689821417 |url=https://archive.org/details/tommysnewplaymat00davi |last1=David |first1=Luke |year=1998 }}</ref><ref name=\"monkeys\">{{cite book |title=The Rugrats Movie: The Rugrats Versus the Monkeys (The Rugrats Movie 8 X 8) (Paperback) |isbn=0689821425 |url=https://archive.org/details/rugratsversusmon00davi |last1=David |first1=Luke |year=1998 }}</ref>\n\n''The Rugrats Movie Storybook'', released on the same date and using the same illustrators and publishers, was written by Sarah Wilson.<ref name=\"wilson\">{{cite book |title=The Rugrats Movie Storybook (Paperback) |isbn=068982128X |url=https://archive.org/details/rugratsmoviestor00will |last1=Willson |first1=Sarah |year=1998 }}</ref> The same date saw the release of ''The Rugrats Movie: Hang On To Your Diapies, Babies, We're Going In!: Trivia from the Hit Movie!'', a trivia book written by Kitty Richards.<ref name=\"trvia\">{{cite book |title=Rugrats Movie, The: Hang On To Your Diapies, Babies, We're Going In!: Trivia from the Hit Movie! (Paperback) |isbn=0689822766 |url=https://archive.org/details/hangontoyourdiap00rich |last1=Richards |first1=Kitty |year=1998 }}</ref>\n\nA novelization of the film written by Cathy East Dubowski was published on October 1, 1998, by Tandem Library.<ref name=\"tandem\">{{cite book |date= |title=Rugrats Movie (Hardcover) |isbn=0613872681}}</ref> The following month, a 144-page guidebook, ''The Making of The Rugrats Movie: Behind the Scenes at Klasky Csupo'', was released on November 1, 1998, by MSG.<ref>{{cite book|title=The making of the Rugrats movie : behind the scenes at Klasky Csupo|work=worldcat.org|oclc = 040590978}}</ref> In May 1999, [[Hal Leonard Corporation|Hal Leonard Publishing Corporation]] released a book titled ''The Rugrats Movie''.<ref name=\"leonard\">{{cite book |date= May 1999|title=The Rugrats Movie (Paperback) |isbn=0634005146}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\nThe film was released on November 20, 1998, and made [[United States dollar|US$]]27,321,470 in its opening weekend,<ref name=\"mojo\">{{cite web | url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=rugratsmovie.htm |date= |title=THE RUGRATS MOVIE |first= |last= | website=Box Office Mojo | accessdate=December 22, 2009}}</ref> from 2,782 theaters, averaging about $9,821 per venue and ranking as the #1 movie that weekend, beating out ''[[Enemy of the State (film)|Enemy of the State]]''.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/12/28/business/prince-of-egypt-is-no-king-at-the-box-office.html?scp=4&sq=The%20Rugrats%20Movie&st=cse |date=December 28, 1998 |title='Prince of Egypt' Is No King at the Box-Office |first=Geraldine |last=FABRIKANT | work=[[The New York Times]] | accessdate=December 24, 2009}}</ref> In total, ''The Rugrats Movie'' made US$140,894,675, $100,494,675 from the domestic market, and $40,400,000 from its foreign release.<ref name=\"mojo\"/>\n\nThe film was released in the [[United Kingdom]] on March 26, 1999, and topped the country's box office for the next three weekends, before being dethroned by ''[[The Faculty (film)|The Faculty]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.25thframe.co.uk/charts/chart.php?chart=19990326|title=Weekend box office 26th March 1999 - 28th March 1999|publisher=www.25thframe.co.uk|accessdate=22 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.25thframe.co.uk/charts/chart.php?chart=19990326|title=Weekend box office 2nd April 1999 - 4th April 1999|publisher=www.25thframe.co.uk|accessdate=22 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.25thframe.co.uk/charts/chart.php?chart=19990326|title=Weekend box office 9th April 1999 - 11th April 1999|publisher=www.25thframe.co.uk|accessdate=22 January 2017}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite news|title= Weekend Box Office : 'Rugrats' Has Kid Power |work= The Los Angeles Times|date=November 24, 1998|url= http://articles.latimes.com/1998/nov/24/entertainment/ca-47071|accessdate=November 10, 2010|first=Robert W.|last=Welkos}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\n''The Rugrats Movie'' holds a 59% rating on the review aggregator website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 50 reviews (30 positive and 21 negative), with an average rating of 5.8/10. The consensus is: \"Charming characters; loads of fun for kids and adults.\"<ref name=\"rotten\">{{cite web | url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/rugrats_movie/ |date= |title=The Rugrats Movie (1998) |first= |last= | website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] | accessdate=December 22, 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] gave the film 2 stars out of 4.<ref name=\"ebert\">{{cite news | url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19981120/REVIEWS/811200306/1023 |date= |title=The Rugrats Movie (G) |first=Roger |last=Ebert | work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] | accessdate=December 24, 2009}}</ref> Ebert wrote that the film's target audience was primarily younger children, and that, while he as an adult disliked it, he \"might have\" liked it if he were younger and would recommend it for children.<ref name=\"ebert\"/> ''[[The New York Times]]''{{'}}s Anita Gates reviewed ''The Rugrats Movie'' positively, calling it a \"delight\".<ref name=\"nyreview\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/11/20/movies/film-review-a-sibling-takes-a-new-rival-for-a-ride.html?scp=20&sq=The%20Rugrats%20Movie&st=cse |date=November 20, 1998 |title=FILM REVIEW; A Sibling Takes a New Rival for a Ride |first=Anita |last=Gates | work=[[The New York Times]] | accessdate=December 24, 2009}}</ref>\n\nLisa Schwarzbaum of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' graded the film with a B.<ref name=\"EW\">{{cite web | url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,285889,00.html |date=November 27, 1998 |title=The Rugrats Movie (1998) |first=Lisa |last=Schwarzbaum | work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] | accessdate=December 24, 2009}}</ref> Schwarzbaum praised the movie for its appeal to both adult and child audiences, \"juxtaposing the blithely self-absorbed parallel universes of small, diapered children and their large, Dockered parents\".<ref name=\"EW\"/> However, other ''Entertainment Weekly'' reviewer Ty Burr gave ''The Rugrats Movie'' a B\u2212, criticizing that the film's issues sprung from it being \"bigger\" than the original series, thus it having more cultural references, out-of-place CGI scenes, and \"[going] into scary territory\".<ref name=\"EW2\">{{cite web | url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,272906,00.html |date=April 2, 1999 |title=The Rugrats Movie (1999) |first=Ty |last=Burr | work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] | accessdate=December 24, 2009}}</ref> Despite these faults, Burr did praise the \"escaped circus monkeys\" for being \"scary in a good way\", as well as a joke that was accessible to younger audiences.<ref name=\"EW2\"/>\n\n==Sequels==\nTwo sequels have been released: ''[[Rugrats in Paris: The Movie]]'', which was released on November 17, 2000, and ''[[Rugrats Go Wild]]'', which was released on June 13, 2003.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{AllMovie title}}\n*{{BCDB title}}\n* {{mojo title|rugratsmovie}}\n*{{IMDb title}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|rugrats_movie}}\n*{{TCMDb title}}\n\n{{Nickelodeon Movies}}\n{{Rugrats}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rugrats Movie, The}}\n[[Category:1998 films]]\n[[Category:1998 animated films]]\n[[Category:1990s adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:1990s American animated films]]\n[[Category:American adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy films]]\n[[Category:American musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Animated adventure films]]\n[[Category:Animated comedy films]]\n[[Category:Animated musical films]]\n[[Category:Animated films based on animated series]]\n[[Category:Directorial debut films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Mark Mothersbaugh]]\n[[Category:Films about missing people]]\n[[Category:Klasky Csupo animated films]]\n[[Category:Nickelodeon animated films]]\n[[Category:Nickelodeon Movies films]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures animated films]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Rugrats and All Grown Up!]]\n[[Category:Rugrats (film series)]]\n[[Category:Films set in forests]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by David N. Weiss]]\n", "name_user": "49.176.187.182", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "",